<body>
    <h1>5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Design Guidelines</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p></p>
<div class=3D"">
<div class=3D"childtabs-macro" data-fixed-position=3D"false">
<div class=3D"aui-tabs horizontal-tabs" data-aui-responsive=3D"true">
<strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data-conte=
nt-id=3D"1203279380">API Design Guidelines</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"cb6b495d-0bce-45b2-a269-40433e29=
828a-1203279380">
<p></p>
<h2 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Topics"><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker"=
 data-ref=3D"ca330a2b-d6a5-44b6-be31-831bda224f59">Topics</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-restful_api_overview">RESTful API Overv=
iew</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-resource_naming">Resource Naming &amp; =
URIs</a>&nbsp;(Resource&nbsp;Naming URIs, Resource Naming Anti-patterns, Pl=
uralisation)</li>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-http_verbs">Use of HTTP Verbs</a>&nbsp;=
(GET, PUT, POST, DELETE, OPTIONS, TRACE,&nbsp;PATCH, HEAD)</li>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-page_sort_filter">Paging, Sorting &amp;=
 Filtering</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-response_codes">Response Status Codes</=
a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-data_representation">Data Representatio=
n in Requests &amp; Responses</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-versioning">Versioning of APIs</a></li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-restful_api_overviewRESTfulAPIOverview"><span=
 class=3D"confluence-anchor-link" id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-restful_api_ove=
rview"></span>RESTful API Overview</h2>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Terminology">Terminology</h3>
<ul>
<li>API - a collection of resources with associated actions (HTTP verbs) pr=
oviding a cohesive suite of functionality</li>
<li>Resource - an object/entity which is the central focus of the intent of=
 an action to be applied</li>
<li>Method/Action - the HTTP verb to be applied to the resource</li>
<li>Endpoint/Operation - the combination of method/action and the resource =
- roughly equivalent to an operation on a SOAP web service</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-RESTfulAPIs">RESTful APIs&nbsp;</h3>
<p>There is a good overview of the REST architectural style at:&nbsp;<a hre=
f=3D"http://www.restapitutorial.com/lessons/whatisrest.html" class=3D"exter=
nal-link" rel=3D"nofollow">http://www.restapitutorial.com/lessons/whatisres=
t.html</a></p>
<p>Here are some key points for successfully offering REST APIs:</p>
<ul>
<li>Use HTTP Verbs appropriately (align with semantics in <a href=3D"https:=
//tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">RFC=
7231</a>)</li>
<li>Provide sensible resource names</li>
<li>Use HTTP response codes to indicate status</li>
<li>Create resources at the right level of granularity</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-resource_namingResourceNaming&amp;URIs"><span=
 class=3D"confluence-anchor-link" id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-resource_naming=
"></span>Resource Naming &amp; URIs</h2>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Summary">Summary</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Use nouns and not verbs in resource names</p></li>
<li><p>Use plural nouns in all cases for collections, i.e.</p>
<ul>
<li>/customers instead of /customer</li>
</ul></li>
<li><p>Differentiate between the collection resource and the&nbsp;singular =
resource, i.e. everything is a resource. Rethink interactions in terms of r=
esource states, not service operations</p>
<ul>
<li>/customers is the collection, /customers/1234 is a&nbsp;single entity</=
li>
</ul></li>
<li>Define resources at the right level of granularity=20
<ul>
<li>don't define them so coarsely that they encompass all information withi=
n a context (eg. the world)</li>
<li>don't define them so finely that a consumer would need to interact with=
 multiple resources in order to collate the required information</li>
</ul></li>
<li><p>Minimise hierarchies past 3 levels: /&lt;resource&gt;/&lt;identifier=
&gt;/&lt;resource&gt;, i.e.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>/customers</p></li>
<li><p>/customers/1234</p></li>
<li><p>/customers/1234/transactions</p></li>
<li><p>/transactions/1111</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-ResourceNamingStructure">Resource Naming Stru=
cture</h3>
<p>An API is a collection of verb actions on a resource set, with supportin=
g data representations. Guidance for the design method, which will assist i=
n identifying resources from a consumer use case and behaviour model, is gi=
ven in the Delivery Methodology.</p>
<p>Resource names should be nouns. It is acceptable to use a verb-like adje=
ctive with the nouns as long as it is still clear that an object, a thing, =
is being identified.</p>
<p>Each resource should have its own URI. There should be no sharing of add=
ress. The resource structure should be predictable (it makes sense) and hie=
rarchical within the confines of usability (it provides the ability to mani=
pulate sub-structures without confusing the user or making parsing complex)=
. Relationships should make sense, if the design method is followed properl=
y.</p>
<p>Resources are generally plural collections, with an identifier as part o=
f the URI to identify a unique resource.</p>
<p>Resources should not bleed information about internal data structures an=
d types, or processes.</p>
<p>Resources can be decomposed into sub-resources (subsets of the primary r=
esource) but attributes of the resource can only exist in one sub-resource.=
&nbsp; Sub-resources are most often used when updating a subset of the reso=
urce's attributes.&nbsp; Refer to the section below regarding the use of th=
e PUT verb for more information.</p>
<p>A more detailed description of resource and endpoint structuring pattern=
s is described <span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">in <a href=3D"https://=
confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/mesh/Pattern+19%3A+API+Endpoint+Desig=
n+Patterns" rel=3D"nofollow">Pattern 19: API Endpoint Design Patterns</a>.<=
/span></p>
<p>Some excellent external articles on resource naming are shown below:<br>=
<a href=3D"http://www.restapitutorial.com/lessons/restfulresourcenaming.htm=
l" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">http://www.restapitutorial.com/=
lessons/restfulresourcenaming.html</a><br><a href=3D"https://www.thoughtwor=
ks.com/insights/blog/rest-api-design-resource-modeling" class=3D"external-l=
ink" rel=3D"nofollow">https://www.thoughtworks.com/insights/blog/rest-api-d=
esign-resource-modeling</a></p>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-ResourceURIExamples">Resource URI Examples</h=
3>
<p>To insert (create) a new customer in the system use, for example:<br>
 POST /customers</p>
<p>To read a customer with Customer ID# 33245, for example:<br>
 GET /customers/33245</p>
<p>The same URI would be used for PUT and DELETE, to update and delete, res=
pectively.</p>
<p>Where a resource represents a process, such as the fulfilment of a new a=
ccount for a customer, you could initiate that process as follows:<br>
 POST /accountFulfilment</p>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-FullyqualifiedURIStructure">Fully qualified U=
RI Structure</h3>
<p>All URIs for RESTful APIs should adhere to the following format:</p>
<p>{base url} / {layer} / {Domain (1..1)} / {Subdomain (0..2)} / {API Name =
(1..1)} / {version (1..1)} / {resources (1..1)} / { sub-resources (0..1)}<b=
r>
 It is recommended that a maximum of 8 resources be contained within each A=
PI.</p>
<p>Example fully qualified URI:&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://api.westpac.com.au/i=
nf/parties/customers/v1/customerSearch" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofo=
llow">http://api.westpac.com.au/inf/parties/customers/v1/customerSearch</a>=
</p>
<h2 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-http_verbsUseofHTTPVerbs"><span class=3D"conf=
luence-anchor-link" id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-http_verbs"></span>Use of HTT=
P Verbs</h2>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Summary.1">Summary</h3>
<p>The HTTP verbs comprise a major portion of our "uniform interface" const=
raint and provide us the action counterpart to the noun-based resource. The=
 primary or most commonly used HTTP verbs (or methods, as they are properly=
 called) are POST, GET, PUT, DELETE. These correspond to create, read, upda=
te, and delete (or CRUD) operations, respectively. PATCH can be used in pla=
ce of PUT where a partial update (subset of fields) of a resource is requir=
ed. Note that POST can also be used as a general purpose 'do stuff' action.=
&nbsp; HEAD is the final HTTP verb currently supported for Westpac Mesh API=
s and is similar to GET but it MUST NOT return a response payload.&nbsp; It=
 is used to retrieve metadata or check service availability for the resourc=
e.</p>
<p>Note: The permitted response codes, and what they mean, for each verb ar=
e described in the <a href=3D"#APIDesignGuidelines-response_codes">Response=
 Status Codes</a>&nbsp;section below.</p>
<p>We summarise the allowed use of HTTP verbs as follows:</p>
<ul>
<li>POST for unsafe to repeat operations (such as creating data or starting=
 jobs)</li>
<li>GET for safe to repeat (and potentially cache) queries</li>
<li>PUT for safe to repeat operations (such as updating data)</li>
<li>DELETE for safe to repeat operations that remove resources (second repe=
at is usually an error)</li>
<li>PATCH for unsafe to repeat update operations</li>
<li>HEAD for safe to repeat service availability checking, response payload=
 size checking, and checking staleness of cached data</li>
</ul>
<p>The following HTTP specs describe the semantics for these verbs which we=
 honour on Westpac Mesh.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231" class=3D"external-link" =
rel=3D"nofollow">HTTP Core Semantics</a></p>
<p><a href=3D"http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5789" class=3D"external-link" r=
el=3D"nofollow">HTTP PATCH Method</a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7396" class=3D"external-link" =
rel=3D"nofollow">JSON Merge PATCH</a></p>
<h4 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Tableofpermittedverbsandresourcetypes">Table =
of permitted verbs and resource types</h4>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"relative-table wrapped confluenceTable" style=3D"width: 87.=
4434%;">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width: 7.62316%;">
<col style=3D"width: 11.3628%;">
<col style=3D"width: 44.5164%;">
<col style=3D"width: 36.246%;">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh"><p>HTTP Verb</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh"><p>CRUD equivalent</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh"><p>Entire Collection (e.g. /customers)</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh"><p>Specific Item (e.g. /customers/{id})</p></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">POST</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Create</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>201 (Created)</p><p>Response to include the i=
dentifier for the resource created to allow a subsequent GET to be requeste=
d</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>405 (Method Not Allowed)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">GET</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Read</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">200 (OK), list of customers. Use pagination, sor=
ting and filtering to navigate big lists.</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">200 (OK), single customer<br>
 404 (Not Found), if ID not found or invalid</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">PUT</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Update/Replace</p><p>(Create is also possible=
)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>405 (Method Not Allowed), unless you want to =
update/replace every resource in the entire collection in which case the ou=
tcome would be:</p><p>204 (No Content)<br>
 200 (OK), only if useful data can be returned</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>204 (No Content)<br><span style=3D"letter-spa=
cing: 0.0px;">200 (OK), only if useful data can be returned<br></span>404 (=
Not Found), if ID not found or invalid</p><p>Note. Technically, PUT can be =
used to create a resource if the primary key (id) is chosen by the Client i=
nstead of the Server but this is an uncommon case. PUT can thus be used whe=
re an endpoint can provide an insert or update, typically referred to as an=
 upsert, but the primary key of the resource MUST be known by the Client.</=
p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">DELETE</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Delete</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>405 (Method Not Allowed), unless you want to =
delete the whole collection (often not desirable) in which case the outcome=
 would be:</p><p>204 (No Content)<br>
 200 (OK)<span>, if useful data can be returned</span></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">204 (No Content)<br>
 200 (OK)<span>, if useful data can be returned<br></span>404 (Not Found), =
if ID not found or invalid</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>PATCH</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Update</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>204 (No Content)<br>
 200 (OK), only if useful data can be returned</p><p>Note. PATCH cannot be =
used to create or delete an item within the collection as the body of the P=
ATCH request contains only the representation of the resource but no explic=
it instruction as to the action to be applied - it will always be treated a=
s change.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">204 (No Content)<br><span>200 (OK), only if usef=
ul data can be returned<br></span>404 (Not Found), if ID not found or inval=
id</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>HEAD</p><p><br></p></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Health-check Read</p><p><br></p=
></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">200 (OK) but without response body=
</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">200 (OK)<br>
 404 (Not Found)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<h4 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Tableofpermittedverbsandrequestparametertypes=
">Table of permitted verbs and request parameter types</h4>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
<col>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">HTTP Verb</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Header<sup>+</sup></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Path</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Query</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Body</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">POST</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted<sup>*</sup></span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">GET</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Permitted</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Not p<span>ermitted</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">PUT</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted<sup>*</sup></span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">DELETE</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Not p<span>ermitted</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">PATCH</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted</span></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Permitted</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>Permitted<sup>*</sup></span>=
</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Permitted</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">HEAD</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Permitted</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Permitted</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Permitted</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Not permitted</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>Key</p>
<p><sup>+</sup> headers should only be used to transport non-functional inf=
ormation (eg. auditing).&nbsp; Westpac Mesh has defined a set of standard h=
eaders to be used and APIs should not introduce their own headers without d=
iscussion with Westpac Mesh architecture.</p>
<p><sup>*</sup> should not contain resource content (this should be in the =
body) but may be used to provide context or hints for processing</p>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-POST">POST</h3>
<p>POST is an unsafe operation in that it typically creates a new resource =
(or may initiate a new job/process). Each resource will be new, so the resu=
lt is effectively different each time as a new identifier would be returned=
 in the data payload (as a rule).&nbsp; When creating new resources the mos=
t common use case is the creation of a single new resource, however it is a=
cceptable to request creation of multiple resources when required (ie. send=
ing an array of items to be created).&nbsp; Note that when requesting creat=
ion of multiple new resources the entire request should be treated as being=
 atomic in that all resources will be created or none will be created other=
wise it will be difficult to form a response indicating which of the reques=
ted objects failed to be created.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;">POST /customers</span></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">POST request</b><span class=3D"collapse-source expa=
nd-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon icon=
">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span></sp=
an><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Confl=
uence">POST /customers HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json
=20
{
    "firstName": "Samuel",
    "lastName": "Johnson",
    "middleName": null,
    "dateOfBirth": "1998-07-03",
    "gender": {
        "code": "M"
    },
    "status": {
        "code": "A"
   }
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">POST response</b><span class=3D"collapse-source exp=
and-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon ico=
n">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span></s=
pan><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Confl=
uence">HTTP/1.1 201 Created
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "data": {
        "customerId": {
            "id" : "12345",
            "idScheme": "CustomerInternalId"
        }
    }
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-GET">GET</h3>
<p><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;">GET is to be used for safe to rep=
eat queries. The use of GET must not lead to a change of resource state, bu=
t it is valid for resource state to change between queries due to other imp=
acting factors.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;">The use of GET shall not require =
any data payload for normal query operations. Use of query parameters is th=
e correct way to search for data. If there is a concern that PII may be in =
the URI and it is desirable to avoid this due to server log caching concern=
s then either:</span></p>
<ul>
<li>PREFERRED: Abstract the PII into the user=E2=80=99s identity and establ=
ish the data as part of the authentication process.</li>
<li>BACKUP OPTION: Use a POST to create a query request resource and return=
 a response ID, then use GET against that ID to obtain the results.&nbsp;<e=
m>Note this is also a pattern for queries which may take time to complete.<=
/em></li>
<li>NOT PREFERRED: Use a POST with query data in the body and return a resp=
onse set to this call.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<p>GET /customers/12345</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">GET request: single resource</b><span class=3D"coll=
apse-source expand-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-c=
ontrol-icon icon">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand s=
ource</span></span><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Confl=
uence">GET /customers/12345 HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json</pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">GET response: single resource</b><span class=3D"col=
lapse-source expand-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-=
control-icon icon">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand =
source</span></span><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Confl=
uence">HTTP/1.1 200 Ok
Content-Type: application/json
=20
{
    "data": {
        "customerId": {
            "id" : "12345",
            "idScheme": "CustomerInternalId"
        },
        "firstName": "Samuel",
        "lastName": "Johnson",
        "middleName": "Andrew",
        "dateOfBirth": "1998-07-03",
        "gender": {
            "code": "M"
        },
        "status": {
            "code": "A"
        }
    }
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<p>GET /customers</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">GET request: collection resource</b><span class=3D"=
collapse-source expand-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expa=
nd-control-icon icon">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expa=
nd source</span></span><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Confl=
uence">GET /customers HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json</pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
