<p>* Only applicable for asynchronous processing, refer <a href=3D"https://=
confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/mesh/Pattern+5%3A+Asynchronous+Proces=
sing" rel=3D"nofollow">Pattern 5: Asynchronous Processing</a>.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;" align=3D"center">The following response code=
s have been considered for inclusion in the above list but dismissed as bei=
ng unsuitable.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"relative-table wrapped confluenceTable" style=3D"width: 74.=
2647%;">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width: 4.23765%;">
<col style=3D"width: 10.4246%;">
<col style=3D"width: 28.138%;">
<col style=3D"width: 57.0387%;">
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Code</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Status</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Purpose for inclusion</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh"><p>Reasons for exclusion</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">207</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Multi-Status</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">To support partial success scenari=
os</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ul>
<li>Part of the WebDAV extensions for HTTP to support distributed authoring=
 - limit HTTP response codes to core set</li>
<li>Response structure is assumed to be XML</li>
<li>Response structure is composed of a single results object containing an=
 array of objects indicating the success or otherwise for each item - our p=
reference is to use the data object to return successful processing results=
 and only use the results object to report the errors</li>
</ul></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">422</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Unprocessable Entity</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">To distinguish between syntactical=
 and semantic client errors</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ul>
<li>Part of the WebDAV extensions for HTTP to support distributed authoring=
 - limit HTTP response codes to core set</li>
<li>400 Bad Request can mean syntactical or semantic errors (original defin=
ition in RFC2616 only covered syntactical errors)</li>
<li>Little benefit in distinguishing between syntactical and semantic error=
s - keeps it simple for designers/developers</li>
<li>400 is the generally accepted response code for client errors</li>
</ul></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">501</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Not Implemented</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Enable the response code for Infor=
mation and Capability APIs, to indicate in a resource/end-point that certai=
n functionality is not yet implemented</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);">Status code indicates that the se=
rver does not support the method/end-point to fulfill the request.<span>&nb=
sp;</span></span></li>
<li>Status code does not align to the use-case need, as the method/end-poin=
t exists and certain functional detail is not yet implemented.</li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(36,36,36);">Swagger is the primary mechanism =
to describe whether a feature has been implemented or not. e.g. if the endp=
oint is not in Swagger it is not ready for production use ; if the brandSil=
o is not in the list of allowed enums, then it is not ready for production =
use. </span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(36,36,36);">Swagger is also the primary mecha=
nism for Service Discovery through Connect, hence the contract needs to be =
reflective of what is implemented and available features.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);"><span>Considering above, Swagger =
should be limited to supported features.</span></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);"><span>Current use-case need is fo=
r internal APIs (information and capability) and the decision is scoped at =
that. If other API layers need to support the response code arises, then it=
 will need re-assessment based on use-case.</span></span></li>
</ul></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p align=3D"center"><br></p>
<h4 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-ResponseCodeDetailedGuidance">Response Code D=
etailed Guidance</h4>
<p>Further details on the codes to be used is provided below, as elaborated=
 from:&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://www.restapitutorial.com/httpstatuscodes.html"=
 class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">http://www.restapitutorial.com/ht=
tpstatuscodes.html</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://ietf.org/" class=3D"=
external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">IETF.org</a></p>
<p><strong>200 Ok</strong></p>
<p>The request has succeeded. The information returned with the response is=
 dependent on the method used in the request, for example:</p>
<ul>
<li>POST: a response body may be returned if required by&nbsp;the use case,=
 though this should be limited to new identifiers (when creating a new reso=
urce) rather than&nbsp;an entire representation of the resource.</li>
<li>GET: an entity corresponding to the requested&nbsp;resource is sent in =
the response.</li>
<li>PUT: the typical response code returned will be 204 with no response bo=
dy as there is no meaningful data to be returned.&nbsp; A response body may=
 only be returned if there is meaningful data to return and in this case th=
e response code will be 200.</li>
<li>DELETE: the typical response code returned will be 204 with no response=
 body as there is no meaningful data to be returned.</li>
<li>PATCH: the typical response code returned will be 204 with no response =
body as there is no meaningful data to be returned.&nbsp; A response body m=
ay only be returned if there is meaningful data to return and in this case =
the response code will be 200.</li>
<li>HEAD: the entity-header fields corresponding to&nbsp;the&nbsp;requested=
 resource are sent in the response without any message-body.</li>
</ul>
<p>This is a general status code, and the most common code used to indicate=
 success where more fine grained success handling is not required.</p>
<p><strong>201 Created</strong></p>
<p>The request has been fulfilled and resulted in a new resource being crea=
ted. This should only be used for PUT or POST. The resource must have been =
created. If creation is pending, then return 202 instead.</p>
<p>We will still provide a resource ID in the response body if appropriate,=
 to support subsequent calls, but if this is not appropriate the API design=
 must support another query mechanism for finding resources.</p>
<p><strong>202 Accepted</strong></p>
<p>The request has been accepted for processing, but processing has not com=
pleted. It may be subsequently rejected. We will only support this status c=
ode for DELETE, POST, or PUT. Call-back queries will be implemented using a=
 POST, followed by a GET.</p>
<p>We will still provide a resource ID in the response body if appropriate,=
 to support subsequent calls, but if this is not appropriate the API design=
 must support another query mechanism for finding resources.</p>
<p><strong>204 No Content</strong></p>
<p>The request has been successfully processed, but there is no data to ret=
urn. This is an appropriate response for PUT, POST, DELETE, PATCH methods w=
here there is no meaningful data which can be returned to the caller.&nbsp;=
 It is important to note that it is prohibited to return any content in the=
 response body when providing a 204 response code.&nbsp; If there is meanin=
gful data available to be returned then use a 200 response code with a body=
 containing this data.</p>
<p>Use of a 204 response code is not recommended for the GET method.&nbsp; =
The caller will expect to receive a 200 response code for successful invoca=
tion of this method.&nbsp; If you are accessing a collection resource (eg. =
/customers) and apply a filter to the collection (eg. postCode=3D9999) whic=
h results in no matching customers found then the response should be a 200 =
response code and a body containing an empty array of customer objects.</p>
<p>Note that the 204 should not be used as a general code for HEAD type que=
ries, as HEAD should provide the same status code response that the GET wou=
ld have given, had it been made in its place.</p>
<p><strong>303 See Other</strong></p>
<p>The resource you have requested is not available at this URI but is avai=
lable at the address identified in the Location HTTP header.</p>
<p><strong>400 Bad Request</strong></p>
<p>The request could not be understood due to malformed syntax or data. The=
 consumer should not resubmit without making changes.</p>
<p><strong>401 Unauthorised</strong></p>
<p>Use this error code response for missing or invalid authentication token=
, but if bleeding through security failures is disallowed, use 404 instead.=
&nbsp; Westpac Mesh APIs should not generally expose a 401 response code as=
 the APIs should authenticate with the backend provider at an application l=
evel rather than user level.&nbsp; However, the caller may receive a 401 re=
sponse code if the API gateway cannot authenticate the caller using their A=
PI key and secret.</p>
<p><strong>403 Forbidden</strong></p>
<p>Use this error code response when the caller is not authorised to access=
 the provider or one of its functions, but if bleeding through security fai=
lures is disallowed, use 404 instead. Westpac Mesh APIs do not generally ex=
pose a 403 response code as the APIs should be authorised with the backend =
provider at an application level rather than user level; this is generally =
referred to as coarse grained authorisation.&nbsp; It is assumed that the c=
alling application will determine whether the user should be permitted to i=
nvoke a particular function of the provider.&nbsp; However, if your provide=
r does authorise individual users for specific functions then it is permitt=
ed to expose a 403 response code.&nbsp; It is also possible that the API ga=
teway will return a 403 if the calling application is not authorised to cal=
l this API.</p>
<p><strong>404 Not Found</strong></p>
<p>Used when the requested resource cannot be found or if you do not wish t=
o disclose that a resource exists.&nbsp; The latter case generally occurs f=
or public APIs where a user fails to authenticate or be authorised and you =
do not wish to expose that the resource exists.</p>
<p>If the requested resource identifies a specific resource such as a custo=
mer identified by the URI /customers/{customerId} then it is appropriate to=
 return 404 if no customer exists with the supplied customerID.</p>
<p>However, if the requested resource identifies a set of objects such as a=
 list of accounts for a specified customer as in the URI /customers/{custom=
erId}/accounts then it is not appropriate to return a 404 where the custome=
r does not have any accounts.&nbsp; Instead a 200 containing an empty array=
 of accounts is the appropriate response.&nbsp; It is appropriate to return=
 a 404 if no customer exists for the specified customerId.</p>
<p><strong>409 Conflict</strong></p>
<p>Use when a resource conflict would be caused by fulfilling the request. =
This should only be the case for PUT, POST and DELETE methods. Potential sc=
enarios for returning a 409 are: resource duplication, optimistic lock viol=
ation, resource is not in an apppropriate state for the action.</p>
<p><strong>500 Internal Server Error</strong></p>
<p>This general catch-all error covers when the server-side throws an excep=
tion. Whilst there are many 500 series status codes, for an API these shoul=
d almost never be thrown. Use 500 only for errors that the consumer cannot =
address from their end.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-data_representationDataRepresentationinReques=
tsandResponses"><span class=3D"confluence-anchor-link" id=3D"APIDesignGuide=
lines-data_representation"></span>Data Representation in Requests and Respo=
nses&nbsp;&nbsp;</h2>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-SummaryofApproach">Summary of Approach</h3>
<p><strong>All payloads must ONLY support the MIME content type application=
/json. </strong>The following exceptions apply:</p>
<ul>
<li>application/merge-patch+json - for use with PATCH verb requests only</l=
i>
<li>other MIME types such as image/jpeg as the response where the content t=
o be returned consists solely of that content type. However, application/xm=
l is specifically excluded.</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-Fundamentalprinciples">Fundamental principles=
</h4>
<ul>
<li>All responses must return the resource data contained within a data att=
ribute.&nbsp; This allows additional metadata such as paging information to=
 also be included at the root level</li>
<li>The HTTP Accept header should expect to receive application/json but ca=
n safely ignore other values</li>
<li>Use camel case for all field names in JSON</li>
<li>Use ISO8601 for date time formatting, i.e.&nbsp;2012-01-01T12:00:00Z.&n=
bsp; Note that the date time value must be returned as UTC time not local t=
ime.</li>
<li>Nest foreign key relations as this allows simple&nbsp; future inlining =
of extra information, e.g.</li>
</ul>
<p>{ customer: { id: 1234} } vs { customerId: 1234 }</p>
<ul>
<li>Use standard names for common fields, i.e. id,&nbsp;modifiedAt, created=
At</li>
<li>Errors should be returned in an error attribute for&nbsp;a&nbsp;JSON re=
sponse. This should not be returned along with a data&nbsp;attribute.This i=
s an array of error objects, each containing:</li>
</ul>
<p>code =E2=80=93 Application specific error code</p>
<p>message =E2=80=93 Human readable description, but not necessarily intend=
ed for display to the end user</p>
<p>details =E2=80=93&nbsp;Detailed information about the error</p>
<ul>
<li>Use <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/mesh/Commo=
n+Data+Types" rel=3D"nofollow">Common Data Types</a> where applicable to en=
sure consistency across all Westpac Mesh APIs</li>
<li>Don't echo information in the response payload which was provided in th=
e request (body/header/path)</li>
<li>Design the interface for ease of use by the consumer(s)=20
<ul>
<li>The API should provide an abstraction of the underlying provider system=
 data models - don't just echo the provider interface in the API interface<=
/li>
<li>Don't design the interface to satisfy a single specific consumer - desi=
gn for all possible consumers</li>
</ul></li>
<li>If there are more than three levels in the JSON&nbsp;data&nbsp;structur=
es, consider your resource granularity again.</li>
<li>If a response (ignoring paging a collection) is&nbsp;more&nbsp;than a p=
age of text when printed out, then consider again your&nbsp;resource&nbsp;g=
ranularity.</li>
<li>Don't be afraid of supporting multiple query parameters. Most consumers=
 will not use more than&nbsp;a&nbsp;few&nbsp;parameters at a&nbsp;time. The=
 size of a generated URI is usually irrelevant to the consumer anyway.&nbsp=
;Let the consumer&nbsp;requirements&nbsp;drive this.</li>
<li>Don't send fields with null data&nbsp;- just don't&nbsp;send&nbsp;them<=
/li>
<li>Make field and property names meaningful</li>
<li>Use double quotes for all field names and values - this is generally en=
forced by the JSON serialiser for the language framework being used</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-versioningVersioning"><strong><span class=3D"=
confluence-anchor-link" id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-versioning"></span></stro=
ng>Versioning</h2>
<p>Westpac Mesh APIs honour <a href=3D"https://semver.org/" class=3D"extern=
al-link" rel=3D"nofollow">semantic versioning</a> principles in that a new =
major version is not guaranteed to be backwardly compatible with a prior ma=
jor version, a new minor version is backwardly compatible with a prior mino=
r version, a new patch version is backwardly compatible with a prior patch =
version.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Westpac Mesh APIs supports both <strong>URL versioning</strong> and <str=
ong>Media type versioning.&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(1,55,85);"><strong>URL versioning</strong> is =
on by default </span>in which include the major version number in the URI w=
hich allows side by side deployment of different major versions of an API&n=
bsp;</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/Solution+O=
ptions+-+API+Versioning" rel=3D"nofollow">Media type versioning</a> is avai=
lable for Open API 3.0 and&nbsp; is a flexible solution for versioning endp=
oints without creating a new major version of an API.</p>
<ul>
<li>It allows versioning individual API endpoints when you need it.</li>
<li>You can version input and output schemas independently.</li>
</ul>
<p>Media type versioning allows the old endpoint to be marked as deprecated=
 and a new endpoint to be created in the same version of the API. Only two =
endpoint versions are allowed before a major version needs to be created. W=
hen a new major version is created , any deprecated endpoints MUST be remov=
ed.</p>
<p><span>You should consider the pros and cons of each versioning strategy,=
 and choose the one that suits your needs and preferences. You should also =
follow some best practices, such as minimizing breaking changes, documentin=
g your API versions, and deprecating old versions gracefully.&nbsp;</span><=
/p>
<p>The use of JSON&nbsp;instead of XML as a data format for APIs provides t=
he opportunity to make many changes in a backwards compatible fashion. &nbs=
p;The table below illustrates some typical types of changes and whether the=
y are backwardly compatible (non-breaking) or not. &nbsp;Note that the term=
 'operation' refers to the combination of HTTP verb and URI.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped tf-macro confluenceTable" data-tf-ready=3D"true">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody class=3D"">
<tr class=3D"">
<th data-column=3D"0" class=3D"confluenceTh">Type of change</th>
<th data-column=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Backward compatible</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Add new =
mandatory request field (query,request body,header etc )to an existing oper=
ation.</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Add new optional request field (query,request bo=
dy,header) to an existing operation</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Yes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Add new =
fields/objects to the response of an existing operation</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Yes&nbsp=
;</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Add new operation to an existing API</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Yes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Rename or delete an existing field from an opera=
tion</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>No</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Rename o=
r delete an existing operation</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1"><p>No</p=
></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change c=
ardinality of a field from 1 to n or n to 1</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Add new =
http status code</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Add new =
error code</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Yes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Enhance =
enum(s) to add more values in request</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Yes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Enhance =
enum(s) to add more values in response</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change m=
andatory request field(query,request body,header) to optional</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Yes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change d=
ata types in request /response</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change /=
 Remove enum values in request / response</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change/ =
remove existing endpoint names</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change /=
 remove existing http status codes / error codes</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change e=
ndpoint verb - example GET to POST</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Note then when a new major version of an API is required, the ne=
w major version MUST include all operations and associated functionality fr=
om the prior version except where this functionality is deliberately being =
deprecated in the new version.</strong></p>
<h3 id=3D"APIDesignGuidelines-MaturityLevels">Maturity Levels</h3>
<p>Whilst being "properly" RESTful requires compliance to a number of archi=
tectural style guides and patterns,&nbsp;what we are trying to achieve with=
 APIs is more important than ivory tower arguments about levels of complian=
ce with the RESTful style guides.&nbsp;That said, the following link provid=
es a good description of a maturity model for Restful APIs which takes a co=
arse grained approach to defining increasing levels of maturity, and how th=
is benefits the integrating systems:&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://martinfowler.co=
m/articles/richardsonMaturityModel.html" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nof=
ollow">http://martinfowler.com/articles/richardsonMaturityModel.html</a></p=
>
<p>The following table summarises the Richardson Maturity Model:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Level</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Description</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>0</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>"The&nbsp;Swamp of POX/POJ"</p><p>HTTP is use=
d as the transport, but without using any of the web mechanisms. Effectivel=
y, this is XML or JSON remote procedure calls (Plain old XML/JSON).</p></td=
>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>1</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Resources</p><p>Rather than making all reques=
ts to a singular service endpoint, we now start talking to individual resou=
rces.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>2</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>HTTP Verbs</p><p>Start&nbsp; using the HTTP v=
erbs as closely as possible to how they are used in HTTP itself</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>3</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Hypermedia Controls</p><p>Introduce Hypermedi=
a As The Engine Of Application State - The message flow defines the availab=
le behaviour on the resource - "What can one do next?"</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>There is a lot more to maturity than just this, as one could argue that:=
</p>
<p>Level 1 should introduce some additional&nbsp;standards&nbsp;for using r=
esources, but the key is to start treating endpoints as managing resources,=
 not providing services, in order to allow the next step to work.</p>
<p>Level 2 should cover off some of the other core HTTP behavior management=
 capabilities, especially around caching, but the key is at this level we a=
re driving the message flow behaviour in line with how the web's client ser=
ver model works.</p>
<p>Level 3 is nirvana and challenging to implement fully with APIs.</p>
<p>For Westpac Mesh APIs, we are targeting level 2 compliance and will supp=
ort level 3 (HATEOAS) for use cases where it makes sense to do so.&nbsp; Th=
e precise design model which will be used to support HATEOAS is yet to be f=
inalised.</p>
<p><br></p>
