<h2 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-FieldNamingConventions">Field Naming Con=
ventions</h2>
<h4 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-DataType:Boolean">Data Type: Boolean</h4=
>
<p>Booleans field names should start with 'is' or 'has'. It should be defin=
ed as type boolean.&nbsp; Eg: Yaml Syntax:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">isIntere=
stBearingAccount:
  description: Represent whether the account receives interest or not
  type: boolean</pre>
</div>
</div>
<h4 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-DataType:Date/DateTime">Data Type: Date/=
DateTime</h4>
<p>All dateTime field must have 'dateTime' in the fieldName: Eg: arrangemen=
tEndDateTime.</p>
<p>All date fields must have 'date' in the fieldName: Eg: lastUpdatedDate.<=
/p>
<h4 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-Acronyms">Acronyms</h4>
<p>All the acronyms must be in upper case. such as ATM, BSB, TFN etc</p>
<h4 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-Abbreviations">Abbreviations</h4>
<p>It is generally preferrable to use full words in your field names over a=
bbreviations. eg. 'previousComponent' instead of 'prevComp'.</p>
<p>Exceptions to this rule would be industry/domain standard abbreviations =
that are commonly used.</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-DefiningAdditionalInformationasKey/value=
pairs">Defining Additional Information as Key / value pairs</h2>
<p>In some cases , it is required to capture additional metadata of an enti=
ty in the form of an array of key/ value pairs.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Field Name</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Description</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Yaml Syntax&nbsp;</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">additionalMetadata</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">It is the additional details required . Eg: for =
creating package ,&nbsp;</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">"additionalMetadata": [<br>
 &nbsp; &nbsp; {<br>
 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; "name": "string",<br>
 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; "value": "string"<br>
 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>
 ]</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-ImportingCommonDataTypes">Importing Comm=
on Data Types</h2>
<p>Many of these common data types have predefined definitions that you can=
 import into your API contract. The definitions can be found here:</p>
<p><span><span class=3D"ui-provider a b c d e f g h i j k l m n o p q r s t=
 u v w x y z ab ac ae af ag ah ai aj ak"><a class=3D"external-link" title=
=3D"https://schema.mesh.westpac.com.au/platform/contracts/0.12.0/common-typ=
es.yaml" href=3D"https://schema.mesh.westpac.com.au/platform/contracts/0.12=
.0/common-types.yaml" rel=3D"nofollow">https://schema.mesh.westpac.com.au/p=
latform/contracts/0.12.0/common-types.yaml</a></span></span></p>
<p><span><span class=3D"ui-provider a b c d e f g h i j k l m n o p q r s t=
 u v w x y z ab ac ae af ag ah ai aj ak">You can import these as an externa=
l reference. For example:</span></span></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">  accoun=
t:
    type: object
    properties:
      name:
        type: string
      balance:
        $ref: "https://schema.mesh.westpac.com.au/platform/contracts/0.12.0=
/common-types.yaml#/definitions/Balance"</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
<h3 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-APIEntityModel"><strong>API Entity Model=
</strong></h3>
<p>There is a definition section in the swagger Spec that contains reusable=
 definitions.<strong><br></strong></p>
<p>These definitions represent the core model of the API and contain only t=
he properties that could be used within the scope of the resources defined =
for the API.</p>
<p><em>Examples: The customer resource for an API designed to expose only c=
ontact information would only define the email, telephone and/or postal add=
resses of the customer along with customer identifiers. It would not contai=
n the IDV status and other demographic properties as they are not in the sc=
ope of the API.</em></p>
<p><br></p>
<h3 id=3D"SwaggerDefinitionObjects-RequestandResponseDefinitions"><strong>R=
equest and Response Definitions</strong></h3>
<p>These definitions describe the objects and parameters that are part of e=
ach resource's request and response. Request definitions include header par=
ameters, query parameters, path parameters and body elements. Response defi=
nitions include header parameters (if applicable), body elements and HTTP r=
esponse codes.</p>
<p>The body elements will contain the definitions from the API entity model=
.</p>
<p><em>Examples: Search customer, which is implemented as a POST operation,=
 and thus the request has a body containing the search criteria.</em></p>
<p><br></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1203279388">Error Handling</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"cb6b495d-0bce-45b2-a269-40433e29=
828a-1203279388">
<h3 id=3D"ErrorHandling-ErrorMessageStructure">Error Message Structure</h3>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">{
=09"result": {
=09=09"errors": [
=09=09=09{
=09=09=09=09"code": 101,
=09=09=09=09"message": "Component not found",
=09=09=09=09"details": "Unable to find component for {componentId}"
=09=09=09}
=09=09]
=09}
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Property</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Mandatory</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Description</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">Code</td>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">YES</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">A specific API code used to identify the type of=
 error. This is not the HTTP Code.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">Message</td>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">YES</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">A consumer friendly description of the error wit=
h context if appropriate. I.e. 'Invalid customer number' (explicit error)&n=
bsp;or 'Missing mandatory field' (implicit - i.e. general due to provider n=
ot providing further information)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">Details</td>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">NO</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Detailed message of the error, usually derived f=
rom provider error message for business related errors. This could be pass =
through or filtered if sensitive information is returned.<br>
 For technical errors this will be defined in the API implementation.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>All errors should be returned in JSON format. Westpac Mesh APIs can resp=
ond with a single or multiple errors.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ErrorHandling-ErrorClassification">Error Classification</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Cassification</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">HTTP Status Code</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Code</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Description</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Business Error</td>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">4xx</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">1 - 9999</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Related to data processed by the API, an error w=
ith consumer input</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Technical Error</td>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" class=3D"confluenceTd">500</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">10000 or greater</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Related to the environment, typically out of the=
 consumer's control</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Process for Mapping Errors</strong></p>
<p>It is the responsibility of the API Designer to work with the Business A=
nalyst to agree on which provider errors are 'business important'.<strong><=
br></strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Confirm whether errors being returned are actual errors and not warning=
 or informational messages</li>
<li>If no errors, return a HTTP response code 2xx</li>
<li>If the error is bad data submitted by the consumer, return HTTP respons=
e code 4xx</li>
<li>If the error was caused by failed processing on the server, return HTTP=
 response code 5xx</li>
<li>Once the appropriate HTTP response code is determined, identify the app=
ropriate error code</li>
<li>If none are appropriate, assign a new error code&nbsp;in the error bloc=
k by allocating the next available number based on the error classification=
 (business or technical)</li>
<li>Provide an easily understood description of the error in the message el=
ement of the error block</li>
<li>Map the provider's error message to the details element of the error bl=
ock</li>
</ul>
<p>When designing the errors in your API, put yourself in the shoes of a co=
nsumer and think about the types of errors you would want to know about.</p=
>
<p>It is important that the occurrence of an error is propagated up the cal=
l stack, but the error detail at each level must NOT be blindly propagated =
up the call stack.&nbsp;You can include provider error details from the dow=
nstream call in your API's specific error block to aid in troubleshooting.<=
/p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Further reading:</strong>&nbsp;<a href=3D"/display/MESH/API+Erro=
r+Handling">API Error Handling</a></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1721951641">Versioning and Backwards Compatability</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"cb6b495d-0bce-45b2-a269-40433e29=
828a-1721951641">
<h3 id=3D"VersioningandBackwardsCompatability-Versioning">Versioning</h3>
<p>Semantic version should be honoured, and backwards compatibility should =
be ensured where possible.</p>
<ul>
<li>Patch version: Minor changes such as descriptions, formatting, addition=
al enums, addition of new fields</li>
<li>Minor version: Addition of new resources or operations</li>
<li>Major version: A breaking change that typically requires a new API</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p>Westpac Mesh APIs honour <a href=3D"https://semver.org/" class=3D"extern=
al-link" rel=3D"nofollow">semantic versioning</a> principles in that a new =
major version is not guaranteed to be backwardly compatible with a prior ma=
jor version, a new minor version is backwardly compatible with a prior mino=
r version, a new patch version is backwardly compatible with a prior patch =
version.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Westpac Mesh APIs supports both <strong>URL versioning</strong> and <str=
ong>Media type versioning.&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(1,55,85);"><strong>URL versioning</strong> is =
on by default </span>in which include the major version number in the URI w=
hich allows side by side deployment of different major versions of an API&n=
bsp;</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/Solution+O=
ptions+-+API+Versioning" rel=3D"nofollow">Media type versioning</a> is avai=
lable for Open API 3.0 and&nbsp; is a flexible solution for versioning endp=
oints without creating a new major version of an API.</p>
<ul>
<li>It allows versioning individual API endpoints when you need it.</li>
<li>You can version input and output schemas independently.</li>
</ul>
<p>Media type versioning allows the old endpoint to be marked as deprecated=
 and a new endpoint to be created in the same version of the API. Only two =
endpoint versions are allowed before a major version needs to be created. W=
hen a new major version is created , any deprecated endpoints MUST be remov=
ed.</p>
<p><span>You should consider the pros and cons of each versioning strategy,=
 and choose the one that suits your needs and preferences. You should also =
follow some best practices, such as minimizing breaking changes, documentin=
g your API versions, and deprecating old versions gracefully.&nbsp;</span><=
/p>
<p>The use of JSON&nbsp;instead of XML as a data format for APIs provides t=
he opportunity to make many changes in a backwards compatible fashion. &nbs=
p;The table below illustrates some typical types of changes and whether the=
y are backwardly compatible (non-breaking) or not. &nbsp;Note that the term=
 'operation' refers to the combination of HTTP verb and URI.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped tf-macro confluenceTable" data-tf-ready=3D"true">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody class=3D"">
<tr class=3D"">
<th data-column=3D"0" class=3D"confluenceTh">Type of change</th>
<th data-column=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Backward compatible</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Add new =
mandatory request field (query,request body,header etc )to an existing oper=
ation.</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Add new optional request field (query,request bo=
dy,header) to an existing operation</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Yes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Add new =
fields/objects to the response of an existing operation</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Yes&nbsp=
;</td>
</tr>
