</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">Change e=
ndpoint verb - example GET to POST</td>
<td class=3D"tf-rowspan-1 tf-colspan-1 confluenceTd" colspan=3D"1">No</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Note then when a new major version of an API is required, the ne=
w major version MUST include all operations and associated functionality fr=
om the prior version except where this functionality is deliberately being =
deprecated in the new version.</strong></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1721952100">Paging, Sorting and Filtering</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"cb6b495d-0bce-45b2-a269-40433e29=
828a-1721952100">
<p></p>
<h2 id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Status">Status</h2>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge a=
ui-lozenge-success">ENDORSED</span>&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-ProblemStatement">Problem Statement</h=
2>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">How do we support paging, filtering and s=
orting of results returned by an API?</p>
<h2 id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Approach">Approach</h2>
<h3 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Paging"=
>Paging</h3>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Paging is generally required when working=
 with large datasets and allows the consumer to control how much data they =
wish to consume in a single call. &nbsp;Note. It is generally impractical t=
o implement paging in an API if the provider (downstream system) does not n=
atively support paging.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">There are two main design decisions invol=
ved in implementing pagination for APIs:</p>
<ol>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;background-image: none;">
<ol>
<li>How the client application will select and navigate&nbsp;to&nbsp;the da=
ta page it needs.</li>
<li>How to partition the response data that the API generates.</li>
</ol></li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Where pagination is implemented there mus=
t be default values supported in addition to value overrides. Consistently =
use the parameter names =E2=80=9CpageSize and pageKey=E2=80=9D with default=
 values for defining pages.</p>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-PageSiz=
e&amp;PageKeywithDefaults:">PageSize &amp; PageKey with Defaults:</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Use a simple pair of query parameters, wh=
ich developers can use to specify pages. If they are not provided, then def=
ault values are applied.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">/customers?pageSize=3D10</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Followed by (for example):</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">/customers?pageSize=3D10&amp;pageKey=3D10=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Default values will depend on the likely =
use case and payload sizes. Also note, PageKey is a string, and PageSize is=
 an integer.&nbsp;</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Response data should include a paging blo=
ck describing the total count, next page details, etc. &nbsp;Example of a p=
aging block is shown below.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>response with paging</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">"data":
{
...
}
"paging":
{
=09"count": integer, //total number of items available
=09"pageSize": integer, // number of items per page
=09"nextPageKey": string, // key for start of next page
=09"previousPageKey": string // key for start of previous page
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Special case Scenarios</strong></p>
<p><strong>Case 1</strong> : If a back end service&nbsp;returns data in a f=
ixed page size, say 30 records per call, and first call will return the 30 =
records and then gives few extra information to indicate the next page set&=
nbsp; as below.&nbsp; The service also does not provide the total number of=
 records.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "nextPageKey": {</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =E2=80=9CClass": "string",</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Type": "string",</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "RestraintAmount": "string",</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "StartDate": "2020-11-08",</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =E2=80=9CEndDate": "2020-11-08",</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>In this case , we still can make use of our pagination pattern. Make the=
 next page key an opaque key so the consumer is unaware of its structure. T=
he simplest way to make this key opaque is to treat the key as a JSON objec=
t, and then base64 encode it and return this value as the paging key. So, t=
he consumer just sees a string which contains a bunch of alpha numeric char=
acters. Using base64 encoding does not prevent the consumer from decoding i=
t if they wish but we should not provide support for any consumer who tries=
 to construct their own paging key. The API just needs to decode the paging=
 key supplied by the caller, ensure that it reflects the JSON object then m=
ap the values to the provider interface.</p>
<p>The paging object in the response will be as below:&nbsp;</p>
<p>"paging": {</p>
<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;"pageSize": 30,</p>
<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;"nextPageKey": "encoded string"</p>
<p>}</p>
<script type=3D"text/javascript">

</script><br>
<p></p>
<p><strong>Paging - Error Handling&nbsp;</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>Example</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Default =
Page Key =3D 1=20
Default Page Size  =3D 10=20
total number of records available =3D  83

Scenario 1:  Get first 50 records=20
GET {{hostname}}/inf/bnkng/resrcitm/itappln/applnrepo/v1/applications?pageK=
ey=3D1&amp;pageSize=3D50=20

'The response should be as below. The previousPageKey is not returned as it=
 is NULL for the first page key. =20
=20
"paging": {
        "count": 83,
        "pageSize": 50,
        "nextPageKey": "1"
    }

Scenario 2: GET  the second page.=20
GET {{hostname}}/inf/bnkng/resrcitm/itappln/applnrepo/v1/applications?pageK=
ey=3D2&amp;pageSize=3D50

The cal will return the remaining 33 records, and the paging block will loo=
k as below. Next Page key will not be returned as it is the last page.=20
"paging": {
        "count": 83,
        "pageSize": 50,
        "previousPageKey": 1
    }

Scenario 3: GET the third page when third page does not exist.=20

GET {{hostname}}/inf/bnkng/resrcitm/itappln/applnrepo/v1/applications?pageK=
ey=3D3&amp;pageSize=3D50
The call should return the 400 Error clearly indicating the page requested =
is &gt; the available pages.=20

Scenario 4: GET 500 records, and if the API can support max 100.=20
GET {{hostname}}/inf/bnkng/resrcitm/itappln/applnrepo/v1/applications?pageK=
ey=3D1&amp;pageSize=3D500=20
The call must return 400 Error with clear error message as 'Can't support t=
he requested page size'=20

</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><br></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">The calling application can then simply m=
ap the pageSize and nextPageKey/prevPageKey from the paging block in the re=
sponse to the equivalent request parameters pageSize and pageKey for the su=
bsequent call.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">DO NOT TO RETURN&nbsp;nextPageKey/previou=
sPageKey if it is null. As a general practice do not return any fields whic=
h are NULL in the response.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><strong>Note</strong> that the page keys =
are defined as strings to support both 'page numbers' and 'last record fetc=
hed' pagination styles.</p>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Limitin=
gresultset(singlepage)">Limiting result set (single page)</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">In the event that a provider is unable to=
 support paging then the result set must be limited (capped) instead.&nbsp;=
 All APIs which can potentially return large sets&nbsp;of data must support=
 paging or limiting of result sets otherwise data may not be able to be ret=
urned to the API (provider timeout) or excessive amounts of data will be se=
nt over the network.&nbsp; Before deciding to support limiting in an API th=
e provider's ability to support paging must be thoroughly explored.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">The pattern to support a request for limi=
ting uses the same pageSize parameter as for paging but the pageKey is omit=
ted.&nbsp; This is the same approach as when requesting the first page of a=
 dataset.&nbsp; If the provider does not allow a pageSize to be specified b=
ut is hard coded to a specific value then the API should not expose a pageS=
ize input parameter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">The response provided by the API must inc=
lude the same paging object as for paging but the only fields which will be=
 exposed are count and pageSize.&nbsp; It is critical that the count field =
is exposed so that the consumer is aware of the total number of rows availa=
ble.&nbsp; However, if the provider cannot expose the total number of rows =
available then the count field should be omitted from the response.</p>
<h3 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Sorting=
">Sorting</h3>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Sorting adds additional complexity&nbsp;s=
o should only be implemented where there is a requirement, rather than by d=
efault. The preferred approach is that the downstream system be able to sup=
port sorting so that the API simply asks the downstream system to provide s=
orted results. The use of sorting with pagination can become complex if the=
 downstream system does not support sorting. It can always be retrofitted w=
ithout affecting backwards compatibility. Where sorting is justified, consi=
stently use the following standard approach using query parameters.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Standard query parameter sort with comma-=
delimited list of fields to sort on, with + and - for ascending and descend=
ing, respectively.</p>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Sortwit=
hSignedList:">Sort with Signed List:</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">/customers?sort=3D+age,+name</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">If the field is a structured resource, th=
en use dot notation to identify the lower level attribute, e.g.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">/customers?sort=3D+age,+name.surname</p>
<h3 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Filteri=
ng">Filtering</h3>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Filtering is&nbsp;specific to the resourc=
e - it should not normally be implemented for all resource attributes&nbsp;=
as it may add unnecessary complexity. It can always be retrofitted without =
requiring a new version. There are valid arguments that for public APIs at =
least the amount of data returned should be able to be constrained to minim=
ise data leaking.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">There are 2 principal types of filtering =
that will be managed:</p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: none;background-image: none;">
<ul>
<li><strong>Limit Response Set:</strong>&nbsp;Limit the records returned to=
 match some value checks, e.g. age greater than 30, or postcode equal to 20=
00.</li>
<li><strong>Limit Response Fields:</strong>&nbsp;Limit the fields returned =
in the response to a set of preferred values. Should only be implemented fo=
r optional response fields.=20
<ul>
<li><strong>Using Views:</strong>&nbsp;Limit the fields returned&nbsp;in th=
e response to a set of preferred&nbsp;values using a&nbsp;named "view" comp=
rising a set of fields. Use when the list of fields is large, but a subset =
of the whole and well known.&nbsp;</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-LimitRe=
sponseSet:">Limit Response Set:</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Each field from the resource which can be=
 used for filtering should be exposed as a query parameter named the same a=
s the field.&nbsp; You should only expose those fields for which there is a=
 clear requirement.&nbsp;<em>&nbsp;</em>The value to apply for the filter s=
hould be provided in the value portion of the query parameter key/value pai=
r, as in:</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">GET /customers?firstName=3DJohn&amp;lastN=
ame=3DTurner</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Where multiple fields are supplied, as in=
 the above example, the individual filters will be ANDed together so the re=
sult of the above query would be a list of customers with firstName of 'Joh=
n' and lastName of 'Turner'.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">By default, the comparison will be an exa=
ct match or equals, however if you require alternate semantics such as 'gre=
ater than' a specified value then an operator can optionally be supplied wi=
thin the value string in the format of "operator:value".&nbsp; For example,=
 to find customers who are older than 30 years of age you would write this =
filter:</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">GET /customers?age=3Dgt:30</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Shown below is the current list of operat=
ors, which will be extended over time as the need arises.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh"><strong>Operator</strong></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Operator syntax</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Comparison value(s)</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">EQUALS (default)</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">eq</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">scalar value</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">NOT EQUAL</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">neq</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>scalar value</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">IN</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">in</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">comma separated list</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">NOT IN</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">nin</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>comma separated list</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">GREATER THAN</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">gt</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>scalar value</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">GREATER THAN OR EQUAL</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">ge</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>scalar value</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">LESS THAN</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">lt</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>scalar value</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">LESS THAN OR EQUAL</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">le</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>scalar value</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">BETWEEN</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">btn</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>comma separated list of 2 va=
lues</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Examples:</p>
<pre>?units=3D7           ; units equal 7<br>?units=3Dgt:7        ; units g=
reater than 7<br>?units=3Din:5,9,12   ; units equals 5 or 9 or 12</pre>
<pre>?createdDate =3D&nbsp; "btn:2018-01-01,2018-06-30" =E2=80=94 created D=
ate between 01-01-2018 and 30-06-2018 (inclusive)</pre>
<pre>?settlementAmount =3D  "btn:200000,300000" - settlement Amount between=
 200000 and 300000 (inclusive)</pre>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-LimitRe=
sponseFields:">Limit Response Fields:</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Filtering of result columns (fields) will=
 be implemented for optional fields using a standard query parameter struct=
ure as follows:</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">/customers/123456789?fields=3Dname,emailA=
ddress,mobileNumber</p>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Views:"=
>Views:</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">A variant of limiting response fields so =
that the list of fields is predefined and given a view name as an abstracti=
on to avoid having to specify a long list of fields.&nbsp; The view can als=
o expose fields not available in the base resource provided thtat they are =
derived from the base fields. This view name is supplied in the URI and app=
ears similar to a subresource but contains a suffix of 'view' to identify i=
t as being a view of the resource.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">/customers/1234567/summaryView</p>
<h4 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"Paging,SortingandFiltering-Advance=
d(complex)filtering">Advanced (complex) filtering</h4>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">When a complex set of filtering criteria =
are required (eg. cross field validation, object hierarchies) consider repl=
acing the filter on the existing resource with POSTing to a new resource. &=
nbsp;As an example, a customer search needs to be able to match attributes =
for customers who are natural persons (individuals) and also for customers =
who are entities (organisations). &nbsp;When modelling the request message =
it would be natural for attributes which only relate to individuals to be c=
ontained within an individual structure and those attributes which only app=
ly to organisations to be contained within an equivalent structure. &nbsp;A=
 sample request body to search for an individual customer would look like t=
he following.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><br></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;"><br></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>customerSearch</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">POST /cus=
tomerSearch HTTP/1.1
{
=09"individual":
=09{
=09=09"firstName": "John",
=09=09"middleName": "",
=09=09"lastName": "Doe",
=09=09"dateOfBirth": "1985-03-27",
=09=09"gender": "male"
=09}
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1203279390">Partial Success</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"cb6b495d-0bce-45b2-a269-40433e29=
828a-1203279390">
<h3 id=3D"PartialSuccess-PartialSuccess">Partial Success</h3>
<p>It is possible for an API to respond with a partial success, with the re=
sponse body containing both a data block and error block (and a pagination =
block if applicable).</p>
<p>The two use cases for a partial success are:</p>
<ul>
<li>The API accepts a list of items to operate on, and only some of the ite=
ms were successfully processed. The list of successful items should be retu=
rned in the data block. The error block should A list of errors with a corr=
elationKey referencing the items that failed.</li>
<li>The API executes a process that contains multiple stages, but fails dur=
ing one of the stages. In this case, a data block may not be returned (just=
 a success HTTP code), but there must be an error block explaining the erro=
r.</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p>Status</p>
<p><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-success">ENDORSED</s=
pan>&nbsp;</p>
<p><style type=3D"text/css">/*<![CDATA[*/
div.rbtoc1773922702545 {padding: 0px;}
div.rbtoc1773922702545 ul {margin-left: 0px;}
div.rbtoc1773922702545 li {margin-left: 0px;padding-left: 0px;}

/*]]>*/</style></p>
<div class=3D"toc-macro rbtoc1773922702545">
<ul class=3D"toc-indentation">
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-ProblemStatement">Problem Statement</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-Approach">Approach</a>
<ul class=3D"toc-indentation">
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-Examplesuccessresponse">Example success resp=
onse</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-Examplefailureresponse">Example failure resp=
onse</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-Examplepartialsuccessresponse">Example parti=
al success response</a></li>
</ul></li>
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-Specialcasepartialsuccessresponse">Special c=
ase partial success response</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"#PartialSuccess-PartialSuccesswithpaging">Partial Success wi=
th paging</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
<p></p>
<h1 id=3D"PartialSuccess-ProblemStatement">Problem Statement</h1>
<p>An API call can be partially successful for a number of reasons (one or =
more downstream systems are unavailable, poor cross-system data integrity, =
code defect, invalid user supplied input). &nbsp;A consumer of the API need=
s to be able to determine when there has been a partial success and react a=
ccordingly.</p>
<p>It is important to recognise that partial success is not a common use ca=
se and in most cases the API either succeeds or fails completely. &nbsp;A g=
ood example of a use case for partial success is an API which accepts a lis=
t of input objects, such as an account balance enquiry API which accepts a =
list of account numbers, and the processing of some of these objects might =
fail.</p>
<h1 id=3D"PartialSuccess-Approach">Approach</h1>
<p>Current design patterns support success (2xx response codes) and failure=
 (4xx and 5xx response codes).&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"PartialSuccess-Examplesuccessresponse">Example success response</=
h2>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>Success</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">HTTP/1.1 =
200 Ok
{
=09data: {
=09=09"field1" : "value1",
=09=09"field2" : "value2",
=09=09...
=09}
} </pre>
</div>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"PartialSuccess-Examplefailureresponse">Example failure response</=
h2>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>Failure</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">HTTP/1.1 =
400 Bad Request
{
=09result: {
=09=09errors: [{
=09=09=09"code": 45,
        =09"description": "invalid input field provided",
        =09"details": "Status must be one of Active, Inactive"
=09=09}]
=09}
} </pre>
</div>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"PartialSuccess-Examplepartialsuccessresponse">Example partial suc=
cess response</h2>
<p><br><strong>Partial Success</strong></p>
<p><br></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: yml; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">HTTP/1.1=
 200 Ok
{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;data: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"items": [ {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld1"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value1",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld2"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value2"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}, {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld1"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value1",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld2"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value2"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;},
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;...
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;]
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;result: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;errors: [{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"co=
de": 45,
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"de=
scription":&nbsp;"invalid account number provided",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"de=
tails":&nbsp;"Account could not be found in XYZ system",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"co=
rrelationKey"&nbsp;: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"accountNumber"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"12345678",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"BSB"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"032733"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}]
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<p>Note. The error object contained within the result object includes a new=
 optional field 'correlationKey' which is intended to be used to relate the=
 error to a specific object/entity, usually provided in the request to the =
API, which caused the error. &nbsp;Using the example of an account balance =
API which accepts a list of account numbers the correlationKey would contai=
n the account number which caused the error.</p>
<h1 id=3D"PartialSuccess-Specialcasepartialsuccessresponse">Special case pa=
rtial success response</h1>
<p>There is a special case of partial success whereby there is no meaningfu=
l information to return for successfully processed items (eg. bulk update s=
cenario) but we do want to return information about the failures, including=
 the specific items which could not be processed.</p>
<p>If all processing completes successfully and there is no meaningful info=
rmation to return then the API must return a HTTP response code 204 (No Con=
tent).</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable" style=3D"text-align: left;">
<colgroup>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody style=3D"text-align: left;">
<tr style=3D"text-align: left;">
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd"><p style=3D"text-ali=
gn: left;"><code class=3D"sql plain" style=3D"text-align: left;">HTTP/1.1 2=
04<span>&nbsp;</span></code><code class=3D"sql keyword" style=3D"text-align=
: left;">No</code><span>&nbsp;</span><code class=3D"sql plain" style=3D"tex=
t-align: left;">Content</code></p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>If no processing is successful (ie. a complete failure) then the API mus=
t return a HTTP response code 500 (Internal Server Error) with associated '=
result' object, as per our design standards.</p>
<p>If some processing is successful and some unsuccessful then the API must=
 return a 200 (Ok) with the associated 'result' object but no 'data' object=
 as there is no meaningful information to return.</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: yml; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">HTTP/1.1=
 200 Ok
{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;result: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;errors: [{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"co=
de": 15002,
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"de=
scription":&nbsp;"Failed to send SMS",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"de=
tails":&nbsp;"Online banking registration completed successfully however fa=
iled to send SMS due to {provider error}",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}]
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"PartialSuccess-PartialSuccesswithpaging">Partial Success with pag=
ing</h1>
<p class=3D"paragraph-353" style=3D"text-align: left;">In some cases , we n=
eed to support partial success with paging.</p>
<p class=3D"paragraph-353" style=3D"text-align: left;">The endpoint accepts=
 a list of ids (some values) as input. The result of this would be a list f=
or each of the supplied values. And for some of the values the records coul=
d be too many.&nbsp;</p>
<p class=3D"paragraph-353" style=3D"text-align: left;">We can use paging wi=
th partial success in such situations .</p>
<p class=3D"paragraph-353" style=3D"text-align: left;">The total number of =
records will be the total records across the list of values passed. Partial=
 success does seem valid too as the values passed in may be invalid (ie. ac=
count does not exist) . The partial success block would only be returned on=
 the first page of results.&nbsp;</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: yml; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">HTTP/1.1=
 200 Ok
{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;data: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"items": [ {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld1"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value1",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld2"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value2"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}, {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld1"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value1",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"fi=
eld2"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"value2"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;},
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;...
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;]
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;paging:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"count":&nbsp;integer, //total number&nbsp;of=
&nbsp;items available across the list&nbsp;of&nbsp;id's passed
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"pageSize":&nbsp;integer, // number&nbsp;of&n=
bsp;items per page
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"nextPageKey": string, //&nbsp;key&nbsp;for&n=
bsp;start&nbsp;of&nbsp;next&nbsp;page
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"previousPageKey": string //&nbsp;key&nbsp;fo=
r&nbsp;start&nbsp;of&nbsp;previous page
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;result: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;errors: [{
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"co=
de": 45,
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"de=
scription":&nbsp;"invalid account number provided",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"de=
tails":&nbsp;"Account could not be found in XYZ system",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"co=
rrelationKey"&nbsp;: {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"accountNumber"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"12345678",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"BSB"&nbsp;:&nbsp;"032733"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}]
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
<h3 id=3D"PartialSuccess-UsingHeaderstoavoidexposingsensitiveinformationint=
heURIandquerystrings">Using Headers to avoid exposing sensitive information=
 in the URI and query strings&nbsp;</h3>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(49,49,49);">PII should not be included in the =
Query String or path parameter where there is a risk that it may be stored =
in logs or on proxy servers.&nbsp; As such, where PII is included within a =
query string or path parameter, it is recommended that the string itself be=
 moved to a header where it will not be cached or logged&nbsp;</span></p>
<p>Example Use cases</p>
<ol>
<li>Sending Credit Card # in the path&nbsp;</li>
<li>Sending Customer email address / Phone Number as a query parameter&nbsp=
;</li>
</ol>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>Example</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: yml; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Example =
1 -  Sensitive Path Parameter=20
=20
GET /creditCardArrangements/arrangementId
Headers:
    protected-arrangementId: 1234
=20
Would be the equivalent of GET /creditCardArrangements/{arrangementId}
=20
Example 2 -Sensitive Query Parameter
=20
GET /customers
Headers:
    protected-phoneNumber: 1234
    protected-emailAddress: abc@email.com
=20
Would be the equivalent of GET /customers?phoneNumber =3D"1234" &amp;&amp; =
emailAddress=3D"abc@email.com"</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Further reading:</strong> &nbsp;<a href=3D"/display/MESH/Pattern=
+19%3A+API+Endpoint+Design+Patterns#Pattern19:APIEndpointDesignPatterns-Pat=
tern19.3.5-UsingHeaderstoavoidexposingsensitiveinformationintheURIandquerys=
trings">Pattern 19: API Endpoint Design Patterns#Pattern19.3.5-UsingHeaders=
toavoidexposingsensitiveinformationintheURIandquerystrings</a>&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"2122193401">Using Headers to avoid exposing sensitive inform=
ation</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"cb6b495d-0bce-45b2-a269-40433e29=
828a-2122193401">
<h3 id=3D"UsingHeaderstoavoidexposingsensitiveinformation-UsingHeaderstoavo=
idexposingsensitiveinformationintheURIandquerystrings">Using Headers to avo=
id exposing sensitive information in the URI and query strings&nbsp;</h3>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(49,49,49);">PII should not be included in the =
Query String or path parameter where there is a risk that it may be stored =
in logs or on proxy servers.&nbsp; As such, where PII is included within a =
query string or path parameter, it is recommended that the string itself be=
 moved to a header where it will not be cached or logged&nbsp;</span></p>
<p>Example Use cases</p>
<ol>
<li>Sending Credit Card # in the path&nbsp;</li>
<li>Sending Customer email address / Phone Number as a query parameter&nbsp=
;</li>
</ol>
<p><br></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;"><b>Example</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: yml; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Example =
1 -  Sensitive Path Parameter=20
=20
GET /creditCardArrangements/arrangementId
Headers:
    protected-arrangementId: 1234
=20
Would be the equivalent of GET /creditCardArrangements/{arrangementId}
=20
Example 2 -Sensitive Query Parameter
=20
GET /customers
Headers:
    protected-phoneNumber: 1234
    protected-emailAddress: abc@email.com
=20
Would be the equivalent of GET /customers?phoneNumber =3D"1234" &amp;&amp; =
emailAddress=3D"abc@email.com"</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Further Reading:</strong>&nbsp;<strong><a href=3D"/display/MESH/=
Pattern+19%3A+API+Endpoint+Design+Patterns#Pattern19:APIEndpointDesignPatte=
rns-Pattern19.3.5a-UsingPOSTtoavoidexposingsensitiveinformationintheURIandq=
uerystrings">Pattern 19: API Endpoint Design Patterns#Pattern19.3.5a-UsingP=
OSTtoavoidexposingsensitiveinformationintheURIandquerystrings</a></strong><=
/p>
<p><br></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
    </div>
</body>
